The locust years of Latin America
Bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is fraying and political instability is growing.
It's hardly surprising since most countries in Latin America have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
The capitals were sold and the national debts were disproportionately increased, but nothing durable and beneficial was obtained.
These years have really been eaten by locusts.
Over the past 20 years, the annual GDP per capita growth in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this speed, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global market except through a timid rise in wages all the time ?
Economic stagnation is the result of bad government, not bad luck.
If Latin America doesn't change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more - a region made up of weak states with large informal economies and very widespread poverty.
Four factors placed her on this path.
Firstly, in the rush for privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, has been sold at auction.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues derived from privatization have generated little in the form of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by a massive external loan.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the borrowing made by national buyers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency represents a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, given that the reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The influx of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would embark on another decade of structural reforms that would try the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of in-depth reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
Governments that operated on technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, inept presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being brought down, property rights are being questioned, and an effort at even more corrupt and random redistribution is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, leading opinion polls in the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic thinking and politics that capital has already begun to flee - even if the elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this may well prove ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks landing hard.
Regarding all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it's doing.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate, which is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the financial outcome economically speaking, because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and a small base to accumulate capital and increase productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the oil-rich years of the 1970s OPEC -- to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is taking a vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that sold their assets and borrowed rather than save.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach nearly 40%, where the current account is in surplus and where there is no public debt.
Governmental institutions are in favor of the market and the population is well-educated, disciplined and flexible in their learning.
Rewards for taking a risk and for initiative are immediate and highly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
His per capita GDP represents only half of that of Brazil.
But with a growth rate of around 15% per year in China's coastal region, it's seriously questionable whether it will surpass Brazil in the next 15 years.
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things are continuing to unfold properly, primarily due to the massive influx of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of accession to the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments backtrack on reforms and the economy loses ground compared to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were flowing in, but those times are largely behind us.
We should therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Populist leaders such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- an Argentine presidential candidate once again -- may come off as a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not be laughing.
